Use Domain-Driven Design (DDD) paradign when organizing classes.
Use a Bounded Context Structure, following this example for a specific use case.

app/DegiroTransaction/
├── Application/
│   └── UseCase/
│       └── UploadDegiroTransactionsUseCase.php
├── Domain/
│   ├── DTO/
│   │   └── DegiroTransactionDTO.php
│   ├── Entity/
│   │   └── DegiroTransaction.php
│   └── Services/
│       ├── ConverterCurrencyToMinUnitService.php
│       ├── ParseDegiroTransactionRowService.php
│       └── UploadDegiroTransactionsService.php
└── Infrastructure/
    ├── Controllers/
    │   └── UploadDegiroTransactionController.php
    └── Repository/
        └── DegiroTransactionRepository.php


---------------------------------

When working with money:
- use the smallest currency unit (cents) instead of the currency itself when storing in the database.
- Add "_min_unit" to the column name.
- Use the currency code after the column name.

Example:
- Price: 147,6800 USD -> 14768
- Local value: -147,68 USD -> -14768
- Value: -125,23 EUR -> -12523
- Total: -125,73 EUR -> -12573

---------------------------------

The services should be named with the verb in the beginning of the name: 
Example: ConvertDataToMinUnitService, RegisterUserService, ValidateEmailService, etc.

---------------------------------

As a general rule, services should always return an object, not an array.
Example:
Instead of:
return [
    'success' => true,
    'message' => 'Data converted successfully',
    'data' => $data
];
Do this:
return new SuccessResponse(success: true, message: 'Data converted successfully', data: $data);

---------------------------------

Use DTOs for all data transfer between layers.

Example:
Instead of:
return [
    'success' => true,
    'message' => 'Data converted successfully',
    'data' => $data
];
Do this:
return new SuccessResponse(success: true, message: 'Data converted successfully', data: $data);

---------------------------------

Try to use SOLID principles when writing code.
Example:
- Single Responsibility Principle
- Open/Closed Principle
- Liskov Substitution Principle
- Interface Segregation Principle
- Dependency Inversion Principle

